        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-21-2.jpg" alt="CHARTS" href="https://www.altdaily.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The job market is showing mixed signals. Employers have slowed hiring, so people with jobs stay put instead of switching roles. At the same time, job openings have increased, showing companies still need workers, even though the demand isn’t as high as it was after the pandemic.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">There were 8.1 million job openings in November, an increase of 260,000 from the previous month. While this is below the peak of almost 12 million openings in March 2022, it’s still higher than the 7 million openings before the pandemic in January 2020. However, companies are hiring at the slowest pace since the early 2010s, when the economy was recovering from the 2008 financial crisis. Layoffs remain stable at levels similar to those before the pandemic. With fewer job openings and slower hiring, people are also quitting their jobs less often than they used to.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Experts see both good and evil in this situation. Low layoffs and a stable unemployment rate are positive signs for the economy, suggesting the risk of a major downturn is low. However, slow hiring and fewer people changing jobs raise concerns about the job market strength.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
