              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is a Minsky moment?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-21-3.png" alt="What is a Minsky moment?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">A Minsky moment refers to a sudden and dramatic collapse in asset prices following an extended period of excessive speculation and overleveraging. Named after economist Hyman Minsky, it describes the tipping point in financial markets when investors, who previously took on increasing levels of risk, abruptly lose confidence, triggering widespread selling and a sharp market downturn.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Minsky identified three stages of debt accumulation: hedge finance, where borrowers can meet their debt obligations; speculative finance, where they can only pay interest but not principal; and Ponzi finance, where debt servicing relies on continually rising asset prices. A Minsky Moment occurs when the system shifts from Ponzi finance to a crisis, often resulting in a financial meltdown. For example, the 2008 financial crisis is a classic Minsky Moment, as excessive borrowing in the housing market led to a collapse in asset values.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
